%N A395362 Walk along the hexagonal spiral, with its cells numbered starting at 0. Begin with no knights. If the square you are at is not attacked by an existing knight, place a knight there, otherwise leave it empty. The sequence lists the squares occupied by the knights.
%C A395362 This sequence is based on a tiling of the plane by hexagons (often called the hexagonal lattice), with the cells numbered in a counter-clockwise hexagonal spiral starting with index 0. A028896 has a picture of the beginning of the spiral, except that there the cells are numbered clockwise.
%C A395362 The knights are Glinski knights for playing hexagonal chess, which can move two steps in any of the six directions followed by a further step at sixty degrees, and so can move to any of 12 cells (see illustration).
%C A395362 This is the analog for the hexagonal spiral of the square spiral sequence A308885. In the latter spiral the knights are classical chess knights.
